							<figcaption>The feedback loop of losing players, resources, and support for a game</figcaption>
						</figure>
					</div>
					<div class="col-xs-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
						<!-- End Wide Image — With Caption -->
						<p><strong>For developers, fewer players mean less income</strong>, especially if their game is free to play and relies on frequent microtransactions.</p>
						<p>This reduces the resources available to the developer. Without a huge publisher willing to push for the revival of a title, a declining population can bleed cash from the development studio.</p>
						<p>So without those resources, support for the game becomes less frequent.</p>
						<p>Multiplayer games are increasingly built on the service and seasonal models, so games without frequent updates become ‘stale’ comparatively.</p>
						<p><strong>For players, fewer players mean longer wait times.</strong></p>
						<p>Waiting isn’t fun.</p>
						<p>After this wait, it is common for games with low populations to struggle to create a fair match. Meaning newer or less skilled players are pitted against highly experienced players.</p>
						<p>Those newer players are likely to then move on to less punishing games.</p>
						<p>Players may decide to leave due to a lack of content or a lack of other players, but both fuel the loop.</p>
						<p>Players consolidate to fewer, more popular titles.</p>
						<h2 id="causes" class="mt-4">How to avoid key causes of tailspin</h2>
						<p>While acknowledging that I am not a game developer, from researching titles that suffer from this drastic decrease in players, I’ve seen a few key themes that can kickstart the feedback loop. This is by no means an exhaustive list, and there are countless other elements to take into account.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Marketing your game without misleading players</h3>
						<p>Marketing a new game is difficult. Setting reasonable expectations for what the gameplay, monetization, and content schedule will be and enticing players.</p>
						<p>Remember to communicate the best possible image of your game, without overpromising and underdelivering.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Avoiding busy launch windows</h3>
						<p>Launching your title amongst other games or expansions, especially those with a large audience due to previous entries, can immediately place your game on the back foot.</p>
						<p>A large and successful launch helps buffer the initial drop games will experience as some players don't stick with your game. Plan carefully on when to best launch your game.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">A fair approach to monetization</h3>
						<p>For a multiplayer game, deciding whether your game will be free-to-play or paid is one piece of the complicated puzzle of monetization. The industry standard for some genres has shifted, so developers should look to see what monetization is popular.</p>
						<p>Further, clearly communicate this monetization strategy. A strategy that is perceived as overtly greedy may net some short term sales, but the long term life of your game can suffer.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Transparent and regular content timeline</h3>
						<p>Gone are the days of releasing a game and supporting with updates months apart. Games now have seasons, weekly events, special daily items, and a constant slew of updates. A multiplayer title with a slower content timeline can be dead in the water.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Manage community expectations post-launch</h3>
						<p>Almost as important as content updates are communicating accurately to your player base when to expect those updates. Open, direct, and frequent community engagement gives your player base more faith in your commitment to the game.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Invest in a stable network</h3>
						<p>It may seem like a no-brainer, but multiplayer games need servers. Without stable connections and players being unable to get into games, people will quickly drop off a game.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Ensure long term progression systems</h3>
						<p>Another sign of the times. Many multiplayer games without strong progression systems struggle to maintain an audience, even if that progression is just for cosmetic items.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Don’t neglect the new player experience</h3>
						<p>Once your game has launched, ensuring new players have a smooth on-ramp is very important. Making your game easy to pick up, and giving options for players of all skill levels, will help build a larger audience over time.</p>
